{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"15486bd0-0b9f-4e55-8ec9-636f857d415e","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request**. In MAUI, there's no equivalent \"request\" boundary — the app has a single long-lived scope. So `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, and your DbContext accumulates tracked entities forever.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives a new DbContext per injection:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Use a DbContext factory** (preferred):\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then inject `IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>` and create short-lived contexts:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _factory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\nThe factory approach gives you explicit lifetime control, which is the recommended pattern for non-HTTP apps (MAUI, Blazor, WPF, etc.).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c871e214-64c8-490f-a33f-a5e320ea4a53","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common gotcha when transitioning from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and `DbContext`. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. But in MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request scope — so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. The DI container creates one scope for the entire app lifetime, meaning the same DbContext instance is reused across all page navigations.","outputTokens":399,"requestId":"F401:D1352:1E3B59D:221D62F:69E81C37"},"id":"c01122eb-0bc6-4be3-b0ad-dfb81e745ae5","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:54:24.462Z","parentId":"be0bca33-77c1-4efb-97e8-d4d1be4be26d"}
